def: A Shakespearean word (used once) supposed to mean the same asrace, a root.
A yellowish amorphous alkaloid extracted from the rootstock ofVeratrum album.
To meet a wager on, as on the taking of a trick, with a higherwager. [Obs.] B. Jonson.

A bitter, brownish yellow, amorphous substance, extracted fromvegetable mold, and also produced by the action of acids on certainsugars and carbohydrates; -- called also humic acid, ulmin, gein,ulmic or geic acid, etc.
To throw as a lance; to hurl; to dart. [R.]While thy unerring hand elanced . . . a dart. Prior.
Not having received the sacrament. [Obs.] [Written alsounhouselled.]To die like the houseless dog on yonder common, unshriven andunhouseled. Sir W. Scott.
To extend; -- applied to a line, surface, or solid; as, toproduce a side of a triangle.
A partner in giving a lease.
Quality or state of being restringent; astringency. [Obs.] SirW. Petty.
The division of Vertebrata in which the embryo develops anallantois. It includes reptiles, birds, and mammals.
